Research Interests My Journey to HCI & DESIGN

Research Interests

Reconsidering User Spectrum towards Genuine User-centered Design

Who is the user always mentioned in User-centered Design? As a UX designer and design researcher, it is important to define the user. It is necessary to recognize the possibility that designers and developers embed their own implicit biases in their assumptions about the range of potential users for their products and services. Therefore, I would like to conduct research that contributes to redefining user spectrums by considering those excluded, such as children, elderly people or those with various abilities. I am also interested in inspiring designers and developers to reconsider and reflect on their design processes and practices.

Utilizing creative and various research methods to listen vivid user’s voice

There are various ways of understanding, but it is essential to learn from users and to base designs on their opinions. A better design based on profoundly understanding users is not created in a moment of inspiration but composed of multistep-inquiries. I use various qualitative and quantitative methods to understand and consider the users and their characteristics by inviting end-users to participate in the design practices. Enabling target users to participate in and contribute to the processes results in the design of technologies that better explain needs and interests and that have an underlying value of democracy and quality.

Provoking debates about impacts from emerging technologies

One of my research interests is provoking critical thought about problems and issues that technology will bring to our society. Technology is not a problem in and of itself; however, problems may arise from how technology is harnessed and embraced in our society. Technology can work either as a tool of empowerment or of inequality; therefore, it is essential to contemplate how to use it. Furthermore, it is important not only to explore methods of using technology in a positive way, but to find ways to predict and prevent unethical or exploitive uses of technology.
